post_text: The May-Port CG School board and administration spent several hours yesterday brainstorming and reviewing our return to school plan for this fall. Our priorities are focused on student and staff safety. We anticipate beginning school on time with face to face instruction. Families will also have the choice to utilize our distance learning model. We have expanded our Chromebook initiative to accommodate our process. We will continue to gather input and revise our plan over the next few weeks. We anticipate our school board adopting a final plan on Thursday, August 6th. Thank you for your continued patience.
text: The May-Port CG School board and administration spent several hours yesterday brainstorming and reviewing our return to school plan for this fall. Our priorities are focused on student and staff safety. We anticipate beginning school on time with face to face instruction. Families will also have the choice to utilize our distance learning model. We have expanded our Chromebook initiative to accommodate our process. We will continue to gather input and revise our plan over the next few weeks. We anticipate our school board adopting a final plan on Thursday, August 6th. Thank you for your continued patience.

post_text: The May-Port CG School district is developing plans to start Face-To-Face learning this Fall. Committees are developing plans to enhance student and staff safety in this uncertain time. We are also working on a distance learning option for families. Please be patient as we develop comprehensive plans focused on safety and student learning. We are also excited to be working on guidelines for the return of activities this Fall. Keep in mind that all of there plans will be subject to change.

post_text: This is an important message from MPCG. We are busy planning for our return to school. These plans include face to face, distance learning and a blended approach. We are recommending that each child would have a minimum of three cloth masks at school. They will be required in high traffic areas. We are waiting on further direction from the state regarding our learning model. You will be receiving a family survey via email within the next few days. Please take time to provide us with this valuable information. If you do not receive a survey by the end of next week, contact the school to update your information. Enjoy your summer and we hope for a safe and productive return to school in the Fall.

post_text: To try and promote an active lifestyle when we are all social distancing, some area schools are trying to get an at home workout challenge started. The idea is that students k-12 will post a minimum of a 10sec video to the Facebook group "Spoilers vs. May-Port CG Patriots At Home Workout Competition" of students doing some type of physical activity such as running, lifting weights, sports specific activity, agility drills, physical therapy stretching, etc. and the school with the most videos approved by their AD wins! Students can use either their own Facebook account or a parents account to share their videos and they are allowed to upload 1 per day for our two day competition. Max of two videos for each student. Each student should upload their own video. Our competition is starting today and will go through tomorrow.

post_text:
Congratulations to our MPCG Speech Team!

Valley City:

Four students on the MPCG Speech Team competed at the Valley City High School Meet on January 11th as their first tournament of the season. Competition involved 21 schools of both Class A and Class B. Ava Nelson placed 4th overall in Radio, and Malena Twedt placed 8th in Storytelling.

Park River:

MPCG next traveled to Park River for competition where they placed 3rd overall out of 14 schools. Individual results are as follows:

Reagan McGillis: 7th in Poetry, 7th in Dramatic
Lily Moch: 6th in Serious, 3rd in Dramatic, 4th in Humorous Duo, and 3rd in Poetry
Teri Nelson: 6th in Dramatic, 4th in Humorous Duo, 3rd in EPR, 2nd in Serious Duo
Ava Nelson: 2nd in Serious Duo, 5th in Poetry, and 1st in Radio
